caption.text:
Let's get real, if you're not paying attention in class and you rather look at this awkwardly captured photo, you probably don't know how lucky you are right now.

Today, only 1% of Indonesian can take higher education. To make it simple, if you're in college, there are 99 who are not.

I believe, living a privileged life does give you a responsibility. We can take action to make QUALITY EDUCATION happen. It's not only about making the other 99% get access to education, but also solving our problems in Indonesia.

So you dont have to sit there, read some news, and keep complaining about how our government sucks anymore. Let's get real now.

Check the link on my bio üêÜ
# AIESEC #Y4GG #LETSGETREAL

If I have to choose who I want to be with until next year, these 10 people will fit the list just right.

Before, I had negative thoughts of each one of my EB mate. I might still have few though. But i realized, this is due to my judging habit. So sorry, guys.

4 days of conference got us closer than ever before. The person whose name is the only thing I knew, turns out to be the person that actually cared about us a lot. The person that I thought was the strongest, turns out to be the person that would be vurnerable and cry the first.

I may not be the best teammate you may ever dream of. Expect that there would be times we fight,  argue, or even not talk to each other.

I am still a baby potato anyway. There is a lot to learn. Maybe after our term, we will learn and a lot and can grow to be beautiful french fries together üòòüçü

caption.text:
May you rest in beats, Nujabes.

Real name: Seba Jun
Birthday: February 7th, 1974
Passed away: February 26th, 2010 (age 36) [Someone made a playlist of his tracks. Check the link in my bio]

It's almost 6 years since he left all of his music legacy to the world. I always got goosebumps whenever his music is on. It is really okay to say that half of his soul went to heaven, while the other half stayed on every piece of his music on Earth.

I first bumped into Nujabes' mixtape a year ago, which I then fell in love with a song called Aruarian Dance, a masterpiece which gives the feeling of how loneliness can be that beautiful.

To know that the artist behind that song died on 2010, back then when all I listened to is K-Pop and dance music. It's not fair that a legend like him should die so early.

I always imagine how music would change if you were still here, Sir. It is an honor to know your music. For that, all of the music I will listen to today will be your creations only.

Make more pieces of you if you ever choose to come back and be an artist once more.

Rest in beats.

#nujabes #sebajun

Day 1 of Limitless Campus
--- A day well spent. I expect this will be worth the time and the effort. Waking up on 3am every weekend for 4.30 shuttle is really okay.

Today, we did about mindfulness training (try to feel, not to think) with Mas Ivandeva. We did a 10 min meditation to help us realize how deep can we feel ourselves. And, OMG, Limitless Campus have their own app! Much respect for kak Rama for making that happen. We also had a talk with Mr. Erry Riyana Hardjapamekas, a sir whose honesty is undeniable. One that could make you believe that being honest will not make you poor, not even once.

The main point of the day is the coach-coachee assignment. I am honored to announce that I will be coached for this entire 10 weeks by Kak Nira, a lady that turned out to be the type of coach that I was looking for. Bear with me please, kak. This will be worth your effort. I hope we can work together to achieve our goals.

Here's for another 9 weeks of surprises!

The chair of MBC, Branham from Ghana, got me flabbergasted. He was one of the nicest and brigthest guy of the room. He wouldn't mind spending almost an hour just to have a long talk with me.

caption.text:
To have empowering others as one of my life values is such a gift from God. --- On the last day of my teaching experience, I remember that there was one girl who told me that I was her superhero. I asked, "Why?" She said because I have inspired her, which then I replied her to keep studying ans enjoying English. The thought never crossed my mind that she would surprise me one day.

Until, one day, the English teacher from the school where I was teaching, told me that finally someone translated my entire farewell later to my students. It was written completely in English with a few difficult vocabs. Before coming home to Indonesia, I told her to give my blangkon to the first one who won an English competition, or the first who successfully translated my letter.

It was that girl. She did what I thought would be impossible for them. She translated all the words with the dictionary she had in her hand. I was very honored and blessed to be a part of her English journey. It was really, really amazing.

I underestimated my impact. I finally have inspired people. I have inspired my students to love English. We were created to be inspired, and also to inspire. I love to be me. And now, I realize one of my true passion, is to empower others.

#AIESEC #SawasdeeProject #MemorableThailand

caption.text:
This project has proved me that AIESEC is worth staying.

I first came to AIESEC not knowing what I should do. When I was accepted, they put me as a staff in Human Resource functional. Instead of working in HR, I was put as an Organizing Committee in Business Development functional's project, Bandung Youth Summit, or now known as Dreamcatcher Summit.

We started this project back then in March. The storming of this team are a lot. We first had our President resigned from her position, we had lots of rejections and problems at finding financial aid partners, the concepts were still not completed, and a few OCs were demotivated and decided to resign as well.

Being demotivated as well, I planned to follow my resigned friend's footsteps, but when I think about the ones who are staying, I wanted to stay. Being an OCVP Sales, I also had lots of bad times which leads to demotivation as well, but I survived it. I have Kak Wine who always believed in me, encouraged me, and kept trackng my work. I have my fellow teammates: Firda, Oki, Inha, Ray, Maraya, who were also stressed out but they still gave me their sales progress with so much detail that I regained my faith in this project. I need to see this project till the end.

I also had my times as PIC of inspiring quotes and captions. Those broadcast messages and quotes you saw, 80% of them were probably from me hahahaha. Muthya, OCVP Program, trusted me as a OC Program on the D-Day to help her. I was very nervous to speak in front of the delegates but seeing them being so passionate about their life, I couldnt help to be passionate as well.

I couldn't express all my feelings and experience in all of these words. It would take a book to tell you all. But if I really have to tell you what I feel in 4 words: "I LOVE YOU ALL"

#DreamcatcherSummit #AIESECxBantex #MyPassion #MakeItHappen #LiveYourPassionPassionately

caption.text:
[Check out my Sawasdee project video. Click the link in my bio]

Good morning, everyone. I never thought that time flies so fast and it's already my 6th week here in Thailand.

Coming here, I learned a lot of things, from everyone and everything I saw and met. I was happy and sad. I was stressed and refreshed. I was inspired and also got the chance to inspire others.

At first, I had my doubt for Sawasdee project because it's already on its 19th (or more) wave now. I thought that this would not give much impact like it used to do. What do you expect from something that had been done 19th times can be better when it's done at the first or second time? But I was wrong.

I had my time as an English teacher in Banthammakrood school at Mae Poen town. From my students and my teacher buddies, I realize that school is really the key to the students future. I want my students to be successful, to do something good, at the very least, for themselves and their family. When some say school is bad because it's not flexible and it makes the students only have one way of thinking, the fault is on the teaching method. Never blame the school. We love our own students and we want everyone of them to excel well, in their academic and their life.

More than a teacher, I'm pleased to be a friend of lots of faces and personalities from all over the world. I'm not perfect, and I had my ups and downs with everyone, but I'm happy. I'm happy to know that I'm not perfect. I'm happy to know that I can do lots of things to make other happy and also, at the same time, I still can do lots of thing to make me better. I love my new friends, everyone of them. Thank you for having fun with me in these short but memorable trip :) And lastly, I've learned that one video can give so much stories in only a few minutes. I fell in love with making video. I wanted to have a life not forgetting every moment. Seems to dreamy, isn't it? But this is who I am. Hehehe

caption.text:
This is the picture that Phi Beer took on Tuesday, July 12th 2016. I want to share how teaching can be either irritating, or fun as hell.

I had a little surgery on my middle finger which leads to a few small post-surgery wounds on my middle finger. The doctor said that I couldn't use chalk to write on the blackboard because he was afraid that the dust will get into my wound. Since it's a bit impossible to use boardmarker since what we have is only blackboard and chalks, I don't have any choice but to write with my left hand. Fyi, I'm right handed.

I had to write so slow to make sure that my writing is big, clear, and beautiful :3 I also prepared some materials to teach the ABC.

In Primary 1 and 2, the kids are SUPER NAUGHTY. They will run around the class or shout just to have fun. But, since my materials are so good, I made them shouted, danced, and jumped around with me. But they still ran around the class tho. It's inevitable.

Thank you AIESEC for the experience!

caption.text:
I met this incredible man in front of 7-11 in Pattaya near the Alcazar Show Building, two days ago.

While I spent 100 baht just to take picture with a ladyboy, I didn't feel the burden I had when I spent some money to buy him and his kids some food and ice cream.

This man was sitting there, selling a few vegetables to earn more money for his family. It might not be much, but he is still so kind to give us a genuine smile to show him how happy he was to meet us. He even spoke English with us. What an incredible guy!

Just when I thought I had lots of problems and struggles, this man showed he stayed strong even when this kind of trial given to him.

Keep smiling, buddy. You're a great dad and also a great man. You deserve more than this.

#memorablethailand
